5.Difference between ALB, NLB, and CLB?
ans:    Application Load Balancer (ALB) operates at Layer 7, the Application Layer. It understands HTTP and HTTPS traffic and can make routing decisions based on URL paths, hostnames, headers, and query strings.
       For example:
          /api → API servers
         /images → Image servers
         app.company.com → App servers
         admin.company.com → Admin servers
         ALB also supports SSL termination, WebSockets, and container-based workloads such as ECS and Kubernetes.
         
        Network Load Balancer (NLB) operates at Layer 4, the Transport Layer. It handles TCP, UDP, and TLS traffic. It does not inspect HTTP requests, so it cannot perform path-based or host-based routing.
         Because NLB works at Layer 4, it provides very high performance, low latency, and can handle millions of requests per second. It is commonly used for gaming applications, databases, messaging systems, and other high-performance workloads.

       Classic Load Balancer (CLB) is the older generation AWS load balancer. It supports basic Layer 4 and Layer 7 functionality but lacks many modern features available in ALB and NLB. For new deployments, AWS recommends using ALB or NLB instead of CLB
*************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************
6. How do you provide cross-account access in AWS?
ans: Cross-account access in AWS is typically implemented using IAM Roles.
     Suppose we have Account A and Account B. Users or applications in Account A need access to resources in Account B.
        In Account B, I create an IAM Role with the required permissions, such as access to S3 buckets, EC2 instances, or other AWS resources.
        Then I configure a Trust Policy on that role, allowing Account A to assume the role using AWS STS (Security Token Service).
        In Account A, the user or application is granted permission to call sts:AssumeRole on the role in Account B.
        When access is required, the user or application assumes the role, AWS STS generates temporary security credentials, and those credentials are used to access resources in Account B.
        This is more secure than sharing long-term access keys because the credentials are temporary and can be controlled through IAM policies and trust relationships.
**************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************
7. What happens when an EC2 instance in an Auto Scaling Group becomes unhealthy?
ans: When an EC2 instance in an Auto Scaling Group becomes unhealthy, AWS automatically detects the unhealthy state and replaces the instance to maintain the desired capacity.
     The health check can come from:
     EC2 Status Checks
        Load Balancer Health Checks (ALB/NLB)
        For example, if the desired capacity is 3 instances and one instance becomes unhealthy due to application failure, OS crash, memory issues, or failing health checks:
          Auto Scaling detects the unhealthy instance.
          The instance is marked as Unhealthy.
          If attached to a Load Balancer, traffic is stopped to that instance.
          Auto Scaling terminates the unhealthy instance.
          Auto Scaling launches a new EC2 instance using the configured Launch Template or Launch Configuration.
         The new instance runs the bootstrap process (User Data scripts, application startup, configuration).
         Once health checks pass, the instance is registered with the Load Balancer and starts receiving traffic.
This process is called self-healing, and it ensures that the Auto Scaling Group always maintains the desired number of healthy instances.
