12. How do you secure workloads running in AWS?
ans:  First, at the network layer, I place application servers in private subnets and expose only the required entry points through an Application Load Balancer. I use Security Groups to allow only necessary traffic and Network ACLs for additional subnet-level control.
      For identity and access management, I follow the principle of least privilege using IAM roles instead of access keys wherever possible. For applications running on EC2 or EKS, I use IAM Roles or IRSA to securely access AWS services.
      For data protection, I enable encryption at rest using KMS for services such as EBS, S3, and RDS. I also enforce encryption in transit using HTTPS/TLS.
      Sensitive information such as database passwords, API keys, and certificates are stored in Secrets Manager or Systems Manager Parameter Store rather than being hardcoded in applications.
      For monitoring and auditing, I use CloudTrail to track API activity and CloudWatch for monitoring, alerting, and log collection.
      I also enable vulnerability scanning, regularly patch operating systems and container images, and use services such as AWS WAF to protect against common web attacks.
      Finally, I continuously review security findings and compliance recommendations using security monitoring tools and periodic access reviews.
