13. Difference between Security Groups and NACLs with real use cases.
ans: Security Groups and NACLs are both used to control network traffic in AWS, but they operate at different layers.
     Security Groups operate at the EC2 instance or ENI level and are stateful. This means if I allow inbound traffic on a port, the return traffic is automatically allowed. Security Groups only support allow rules.

     NACLs (Network Access Control Lists) operate at the subnet level and are stateless. This means I must explicitly allow both inbound and outbound traffic. NACLs support both allow and deny rules and are evaluated in rule number order.
     Security Group Use Case
         Suppose I have an Application Load Balancer and application servers.
         I can configure the application server Security Group to allow port 8080 traffic only from the ALB Security Group.
         This ensures nobody can directly access the application servers even if they know the private IP.
     NACL Use Case
         Suppose my company wants to block traffic from a specific IP range due to suspicious activity.
         Security Groups cannot create deny rules, but NACLs can.
         I can add a deny rule in the NACL to block that IP range before traffic even reaches any EC2 instances in the subnet.
     In general, Security Groups act as the first line of defense for individual instances, while NACLs provide an additional layer of security at the subnet level.
