14. How do you troubleshoot high CPU utilization on an EC2 instance?
ans: When I notice high CPU utilization on an EC2 instance, I first verify the issue using CloudWatch metrics. I check whether the CPU spike is sudden, continuous, or occurs only during specific time periods.
     Next, I connect to the instance using Session Manager or SSH and identify the process consuming the CPU using commands such as:
         top
         htop
         ps -eo pid,ppid,cmd,%mem,%cpu --sort=-%cpu
    Once I identify the process, I determine whether it is expected application behavior or an abnormal process.
   Then I check the application logs, system logs, and web server logs to understand why the process is consuming high CPU. I also verify whether there were recent deployments, configuration changes, batch jobs, or increased user traffic.
   if the issue is application-related, I coordinate with the development team and provide logs, metrics, and timestamps for analysis.
   If the traffic increase is legitimate, I may temporarily scale out using Auto Scaling Groups or increase instance capacity while the root cause is being investigated.
   If a rogue process is causing the issue and it is safe to do so, I can stop or restart the process after following the change management process.
   Finally, I implement preventive measures such as CloudWatch alarms, Auto Scaling policies, and application performance monitoring to avoid future incidents.
