     First, I created a Launch Template containing the AMI, instance type, Security Groups, IAM role, key pair, and User Data scripts required to bootstrap the application when a new instance is launched.
     Then I created an Auto Scaling Group across multiple Availability Zones and attached it to an Application Load Balancer target group. This ensures traffic is distributed only to healthy instances.
     We configured a minimum capacity of 2 instances, a desired capacity of 2, and a maximum capacity of 6 instances.
    For scaling policies, we used CloudWatch metrics. For example:
          Scale out when CPU utilization is above 70% for 5 minutes.
          Scale in when CPU utilization drops below 30% for a specific period.
    When traffic increased, Auto Scaling automatically launched additional instances using the Launch Template and registered them with the Load Balancer. When traffic reduced, unnecessary instances were terminated automatically.
    This helped us handle traffic spikes without manual intervention while also reducing infrastructure costs during low-usage periods.
